00:42:18,367 --> 00:42:19,187
I can take some questions?

968
00:42:19,848 --> 00:42:20,108
Cool.

969
00:42:20,328 --> 00:42:20,748
Hey, Alexander.

970
00:42:20,768 --> 00:42:20,928
Hey, Matt.

971
00:42:21,842 --> 00:42:23,243
Hey Alexander, over here to your right.

972
00:42:24,804 --> 00:42:26,685
So you talked an awful lot and it was really awesome

973
00:42:26,725 --> 00:42:28,866
about how your personality and your PR strategy

974
00:42:29,046 --> 00:42:32,088
and your iterations led to the success of your game.

975
00:42:32,268 --> 00:42:33,809
You only talked a little bit about how the nature

976
00:42:33,909 --> 00:42:35,930
of your game itself led to the success of the game.

977
00:42:35,970 --> 00:42:37,491
Is there anything that you would sort of like

978
00:42:37,912 --> 00:42:43,575
in high concept add that like, on that point basically?

979
00:42:43,655 --> 00:42:47,397
Yes, this is what this next talk is about.

980
00:42:47,437 --> 00:42:49,078
There was way too much to talk about today.

981
00:42:51,315 --> 00:42:54,877
I had a lot of people who, like with the luck thing, would be looking at my game

982
00:42:56,117 --> 00:42:59,419
as I'm talking about chasing opportunities, as I'm talking about going through festivals and stuff.

983
00:43:00,119 --> 00:43:02,100
And they'd be like, well yeah, but come on, you just had a good game.

984
00:43:02,660 --> 00:43:06,221
But actually back in 2009, I didn't have a really good game.

985
00:43:06,642 --> 00:43:09,443
A lot of the feedback that I was getting on that version, it worked as a mod.

986
00:43:09,603 --> 00:43:10,543
It worked as a free mod.

987
00:43:10,923 --> 00:43:12,544
And it worked for things like Make Something Unreal.

988
00:43:12,564 --> 00:43:13,965
And it worked for things like Sense of Wonder Knight,

989
00:43:13,985 --> 00:43:17,586
which were looking for these really abstract, unconventional things.

990
00:43:17,626 --> 00:43:20,307
But when I decided to take that and turn it into a standalone thing,

991
00:43:22,096 --> 00:43:24,817
The feedback that I got from absolutely everyone was like,

992
00:43:25,937 --> 00:43:28,138
I'm always lost, there's too many dead ends,

993
00:43:28,498 --> 00:43:31,259
I don't know where to go, puzzles should flash red if I can't do them,

994
00:43:31,419 --> 00:43:33,179
you know, the whole game should be restructured.

995
00:43:33,999 --> 00:43:35,360
And I had people asking this question,

996
00:43:36,280 --> 00:43:37,660
when I'm trying to solve some of this stuff,

997
00:43:38,661 --> 00:43:41,441
they'd be like, yeah, but well, do you want to make something new,

998
00:43:41,781 --> 00:43:43,182
or do you want to make something that can sell?

999
00:43:43,402 --> 00:43:45,022
And I was like, no, I actually want both.

1000
00:43:45,622 --> 00:43:47,383
And so by going through things like E3,

1001
00:43:47,803 --> 00:43:49,163
and watching people play the game,

1002
00:43:50,097 --> 00:43:54,121
I was able to identify all of the issues that were coming up and that were problems,

1003
00:43:54,241 --> 00:43:57,484
and then just be spot-fixing them all, and then I'd put it in front of people again,

1004
00:43:57,504 --> 00:43:59,986
and I'd watch all of those things. I'd see what they thought was interesting.

1005
00:44:00,347 --> 00:44:02,629
I'd remove the parts they thought were uninteresting.

1006
00:44:02,649 --> 00:44:06,692
And part of my talk tomorrow is about designing this balance

1007
00:44:06,732 --> 00:44:09,175
between making something remarkable and making something commercial.

1008
00:44:10,283 --> 00:44:13,644
Ultimately, one of the takeaways there is that the further you decide to go

1009
00:44:14,204 --> 00:44:16,685
in the remarkable direction, away from what the industry supports,

1010
00:44:17,245 --> 00:44:20,567
the more work you have to do to bring it back and make people understand

1011
00:44:20,647 --> 00:44:22,968
why they should care about this thing, which is a lot of work.

1012
00:44:23,548 --> 00:44:26,349
But the flip side of that is that it's also a lot of work to start with something

1013
00:44:26,369 --> 00:44:29,570
that you think will be commercial because you're attacking a market that already exists.

1014
00:44:29,990 --> 00:44:33,191
Now you need to do all of the work of proving why people should care about your game

1015
00:44:33,431 --> 00:44:36,152
more than some of these other games that have bigger marketing budgets,

1016
00:44:36,192 --> 00:44:38,313
that have executed things better, that have sequels to...

1017
00:44:38,853 --> 00:44:39,614
you know, things like that.

1018
00:44:39,654 --> 00:44:42,415
And so for me, it made sense to try and just push

1019
00:44:42,455 --> 00:44:45,316
in this remarkable direction and then work out

1020
00:44:45,536 --> 00:44:46,156
what I had to do there.

1021
00:44:46,176 --> 00:44:46,837
And I was doing it.

1022
00:44:47,297 --> 00:44:49,738
I brought up examples of Braid and World of Goo and Portal.

1023
00:44:49,818 --> 00:44:51,478
And I did that because they were also games

1024
00:44:51,538 --> 00:44:53,399
that happened to meet these balance.

1025
00:44:53,439 --> 00:44:55,860
And I wanted to understand not just what the games did,

1026
00:44:55,900 --> 00:44:58,361
but what led them to making all of those decisions

1027
00:44:58,401 --> 00:44:59,201
and do the same thing.

1028
00:44:59,982 --> 00:45:00,662
That was great, man. Thanks.

1029
00:45:00,942 --> 00:45:01,202
Thank you.

1030
00:45:03,663 --> 00:45:04,623
Go ahead.

1031
00:45:05,604 --> 00:45:06,264
Was it worth it?

1032
00:45:10,494 --> 00:45:12,721
Honestly, for a long time,

1033
00:45:14,025 --> 00:45:15,169
the answer to that question was,

1034
00:45:15,229 --> 00:45:15,911
I'm not so sure.

1035
00:45:19,022 --> 00:45:21,565
I posted about how much of a success this thing was,

1036
00:45:22,105 --> 00:45:23,927
and one of the fastest lessons that you learn

1037
00:45:24,247 --> 00:45:26,490
is that having a large bank account does absolutely nothing

1038
00:45:26,530 --> 00:45:27,671
to solve a lot of your problems,

1039
00:45:28,231 --> 00:45:30,754
and in fact it just gives you a hell of a lot more problems.

1040
00:45:30,814 --> 00:45:33,997
It affected relationships with a bunch of people.

1041
00:45:34,698 --> 00:45:38,021
I was obviously going through some pretty big mental issues

1042
00:45:38,061 --> 00:45:38,842
going through all of this,

1043
00:45:39,563 --> 00:45:41,505
and then when I'm talking with people,

1044
00:45:42,045 --> 00:45:43,547
if I'm not the kind of person that's always...

1045
00:45:44,726 --> 00:45:46,567
very candid and honest about my problems

1046
00:45:47,168 --> 00:45:49,770
and suddenly my problems revolve around money

1047
00:45:50,190 --> 00:45:53,373
then you start getting people being like man I wish I had your problems and I'd be like

1048
00:45:53,873 --> 00:45:57,296
really like you want to be completely physically sick and have mental health issues and

1049
00:45:57,656 --> 00:45:59,378
be screaming at yourself in the mirror and

1050
00:45:59,618 --> 00:46:02,680
you know fuck up your relationship with people I don't know why the hell you would want that

1051
00:46:03,767 --> 00:46:06,631
But, you know, the fault isn't on them for that.

1052
00:46:06,671 --> 00:46:08,993
Obviously they can't understand these circumstances.

1053
00:46:09,053 --> 00:46:12,557
And so, what I decided to do, having gone through all of this,

1054
00:46:12,597 --> 00:46:13,578
and having struggled through this,

1055
00:46:13,858 --> 00:46:15,000
the answer now is obviously,

1056
00:46:16,261 --> 00:46:20,125
it took a long time, but I am now in a much better position.

1057
00:46:20,145 --> 00:46:21,547
I am in the position I wanted to be.

1058
00:46:22,610 --> 00:46:23,991
be in when I decided to do this.

1059
00:46:24,572 --> 00:46:26,753
But now when other people are releasing their games,

1060
00:46:27,254 --> 00:46:29,335
or when they do have these big successes,

1061
00:46:29,355 --> 00:46:32,037
I'm there day one to try and talk to them

1062
00:46:32,077 --> 00:46:33,078
and help them out and say,

1063
00:46:33,238 --> 00:46:35,080
this is what the future could be like for you,

1064
00:46:35,120 --> 00:46:36,881
so they don't have to go through the same problems I did.

1065
00:46:37,722 --> 00:46:38,702
Thanks for all your honesty.

1066
00:46:41,524 --> 00:46:42,325
How did...

1067
00:46:43,006 --> 00:46:43,666
Me in the middle here.

1068
00:46:45,387 --> 00:46:47,509
How did you support yourself financially while doing this?

1069
00:46:48,227 --> 00:46:52,991
So I went into this with $17,000 in savings, and I had that, all of this is like five-year

1070
00:46:53,052 --> 00:46:53,632
plan stuff.

1071
00:46:54,193 --> 00:46:59,078
So when I was working in industry, I was just in, like a junior or an intern, whatever,

1072
00:46:59,538 --> 00:47:00,399
and I was on like a $28,000 salary.

1073
00:47:04,486 --> 00:47:08,671
Some of that would have gone into tax, and then I would have only spent about a couple of thousand dollars throughout that year,

1074
00:47:08,751 --> 00:47:11,634
thinking, I don't need any of this now, and I'm not very materialistic,

1075
00:47:11,674 --> 00:47:14,837
so I'm just going to put all of this in the bank, if I happen to need it one day.

1076
00:47:15,297 --> 00:47:17,399
So when I needed to go to things like Sense of Wonder Night,

1077
00:47:17,740 --> 00:47:20,903
I just had this $17,000 there, that I could use.

1078
00:47:21,263 --> 00:47:23,085
And then when I got the money from Make Something Unreal,

1079
00:47:23,806 --> 00:47:27,049
that gave me another $25,000, so I could continue extending things out.

1080
00:47:27,964 --> 00:47:29,926
And then as I continued going through these competitions,

1081
00:47:30,646 --> 00:47:34,149
some of them came with money, but most of them came with, like, free booth space.

1082
00:47:34,189 --> 00:47:36,791
So I was never paying for most of my booths around all of this.

1083
00:47:37,571 --> 00:47:40,513
And being from Australia, there was also some government grants,

1084
00:47:40,553 --> 00:47:42,695
which weren't for, like, outright funding.

1085
00:47:42,715 --> 00:47:44,536
There were things like, if you go to an event

1086
00:47:44,916 --> 00:47:46,658
and you need to recoup some of your expenses,

1087
00:47:46,678 --> 00:47:49,300
you can get a grant that will recoup, like, $2,500.

1088
00:47:49,980 --> 00:47:52,702
So, for example, when I went to the PAX 10 in 2011,

1089
00:47:53,082 --> 00:47:55,344
I was actually really out of money at that stage.

1090
00:47:56,750 --> 00:48:01,634
But going to that, it cost me $2,300 in flights,

1091
00:48:02,134 --> 00:48:04,536
and I spent $300 while I was there,

1092
00:48:05,237 --> 00:48:06,938
but I stayed with friends.

1093
00:48:06,978 --> 00:48:08,380
I always stayed with friends when I was traveling,

1094
00:48:08,400 --> 00:48:10,001
because that means I don't have to pay for accommodation,

1095
00:48:10,381 --> 00:48:11,602
and I didn't have to pay for my booth,

1096
00:48:11,642 --> 00:48:12,603
because it was covered by packs.

1097
00:48:13,904 --> 00:48:17,625
which meant that I was able to then go to the government and recoup two and a half thousand dollars

1098
00:48:18,066 --> 00:48:21,487
in expenses, which happened to make that whole trip just completely free.

1099
00:48:22,027 --> 00:48:23,528
So I was being as frugal as I could.

1100
00:48:23,548 --> 00:48:27,109
I was also living at home with parents, which kept my burn rate very low.

1101
00:48:27,649 --> 00:48:29,970
And I understand that, you know, not everyone is in that position,

1102
00:48:30,010 --> 00:48:34,052
but honestly, funding is one of the most solved problems in independent development.

1103
00:48:34,072 --> 00:48:35,792
You can go to publishers, you can get kickstarted.

1104
00:48:35,812 --> 00:48:38,713
There is government grants, there is, you know, private, private funding.

1105
00:48:38,773 --> 00:48:39,594
There's pre-orders, etc.

1106
00:48:40,634 --> 00:48:41,915
If people look at funding and say,

1107
00:48:41,935 --> 00:48:43,075
oh, but you just lived with parents,

1108
00:48:43,095 --> 00:48:45,216
that was an active decision on my behalf

1109
00:48:45,256 --> 00:48:47,037
to stay doing that to keep my burn rate very low.

1110
00:48:47,057 --> 00:48:48,498
Thank you much.

1111
00:48:51,439 --> 00:48:53,080
Um, so my question is,

1112
00:48:53,320 --> 00:48:56,382
uh, you talk about how, um, a lot of the promotion

1113
00:48:56,802 --> 00:48:57,642
and, like, meeting people,

1114
00:48:57,682 --> 00:48:59,243
you had to go to all these conferences,

1115
00:48:59,583 --> 00:49:01,324
um, and festivals and everything.

1116
00:49:01,404 --> 00:49:03,345
I wanted to know how you were able to structure

1117
00:49:03,365 --> 00:49:05,947
your, uh, development cycle around that

1118
00:49:06,067 --> 00:49:08,488
so that it didn't really mess with, um...

1119
00:49:09,225 --> 00:49:12,406
you didn't go away for a week and come back and that didn't really disrupt you.

1120
00:49:12,867 --> 00:49:16,968
So the thing that festivals were solving is when I was just alone in my bedroom,

1121
00:49:17,448 --> 00:49:19,249
that's actually when things were the most difficult.

1122
00:49:19,569 --> 00:49:22,970
And every time I went off to a festival, I would be completely refreshed

1123
00:49:23,070 --> 00:49:25,431
and I was still working the whole time.

1124
00:49:25,571 --> 00:49:28,052
I was networking, I was doing business, I was...

1125
00:49:29,818 --> 00:49:33,679
testing the game constantly and that was the most valuable work that I did and it's also

1126
00:49:33,719 --> 00:49:37,260
what refreshed my mental state so that then I could come back and work on the problems

1127
00:49:37,320 --> 00:49:41,121
that were real problems, you know. After a couple of months you start thinking these

1128
00:49:41,141 --> 00:49:44,422
are the most significant problems, I really need to fix these things. You'd go to a festival

1129
00:49:44,442 --> 00:49:48,643
and realize actually none of that work matters, no one cares about any of that stuff. And

1130
00:49:48,663 --> 00:49:52,183
so it was also making me much more efficient because it stopped me working on things that

1131
00:49:52,543 --> 00:49:53,784
just didn't matter in the long run.

1132
00:49:58,057 --> 00:50:00,838
I'm not sure if you can talk about them or to the extent you can talk about them,

1133
00:50:01,018 --> 00:50:04,879
but from someone who went through a seven-year development cycle and had so many problems

1134
00:50:04,939 --> 00:50:08,840
and went through so much, where do you... I'm just curious, where do you go from here?

1135
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:13,462
You know, is it difficult to like think about having another seven-year development cycle,

1136
00:50:13,482 --> 00:50:18,844
have another game that, you know, is that difficult? What do you... what's your thoughts now?

1137
00:50:20,492 --> 00:50:23,673
This is part of why some of this was problematic.

1138
00:50:23,914 --> 00:50:25,074
You know, after releasing this,

1139
00:50:25,094 --> 00:50:26,235
a whole lot of people were like,

1140
00:50:26,355 --> 00:50:27,575
oh man, what are you going to work on next?

1141
00:50:27,635 --> 00:50:29,737
And I'm like, if this is how I feel

1142
00:50:30,177 --> 00:50:32,338
after the one that just pulled off absolutely everything,

1143
00:50:32,358 --> 00:50:34,239
I don't want to do this again.

1144
00:50:34,259 --> 00:50:36,100
You know, fuck that.

1145
00:50:36,260 --> 00:50:36,560
And so...

1146
00:50:38,830 --> 00:50:40,391
That lost all of my creative drive.

1147
00:50:40,972 --> 00:50:43,314
And if I was also doing this for the career drive,

1148
00:50:43,594 --> 00:50:45,495
and for like the financial side, and I've just solved that,

1149
00:50:45,535 --> 00:50:47,197
I lost all of my financial drive as well.

1150
00:50:47,977 --> 00:50:49,739
Which means that you've taken a very driven person

1151
00:50:49,779 --> 00:50:52,361
and you've removed any reason for them to have drive.

1152
00:50:52,441 --> 00:50:55,344
And honestly, that just took a whole lot of time.

1153
00:50:55,364 --> 00:50:56,925
It would have taken eight months

1154
00:50:56,985 --> 00:50:59,327
before I started becoming interested in anything again.

1155
00:50:59,387 --> 00:51:00,708
And that was something that I couldn't force.

1156
00:51:00,748 --> 00:51:02,009
I can't intensely problem-solve

1157
00:51:02,029 --> 00:51:03,230
being interested about the world.

1158
00:51:03,851 --> 00:51:04,351
I just have to...

1159
00:51:05,612 --> 00:51:07,914
I just had to live more existentially day to day

1160
00:51:08,194 --> 00:51:09,675
and just find other things that would interest me.

1161
00:51:10,296 --> 00:51:12,297
Thank you. You're welcome.

1162
00:51:12,357 --> 00:51:13,859
Hey, Alex. I'm Hamish.

1163
00:51:15,620 --> 00:51:16,601
My question is, what...

1164
00:51:16,961 --> 00:51:18,502
and you might be addressing this tomorrow,

1165
00:51:18,522 --> 00:51:19,783
but I feel like I have to know now.

1166
00:51:20,184 --> 00:51:22,406
What percentage of your development time

1167
00:51:22,446 --> 00:51:24,848
were you spending on this kind of stuff,

1168
00:51:24,888 --> 00:51:25,928
on marketing, basically?

1169
00:51:26,429 --> 00:51:28,971
On marketing and testing? So I would have gone through...

1170
00:51:28,991 --> 00:51:29,711
No, just marketing.

1171
00:51:31,867 --> 00:51:33,369
they were kind of the same.

1172
00:51:33,389 --> 00:51:36,172
Like, going to events was testing as well.

1173
00:51:36,432 --> 00:51:37,754
So, on marketing and stuff.

1174
00:51:37,774 --> 00:51:39,075
So, it was primarily through events.

1175
00:51:39,415 --> 00:51:41,137
So, I went through like 15 to 20 events

1176
00:51:41,658 --> 00:51:43,800
before I'd released the game.

1177
00:51:43,881 --> 00:51:47,064
And that, those things are only very short bursts.

1178
00:51:47,124 --> 00:51:49,146
Maybe they're three days, maybe they're a week.

1179
00:51:50,157 --> 00:51:52,939
And then between all of those, I was just straight back on the development.

1180
00:51:53,359 --> 00:51:56,901
And as I was submitting builds to festivals,

1181
00:51:57,301 --> 00:51:59,002
then I would have to do a little bit more work,

1182
00:51:59,062 --> 00:52:01,563
then, on, like, information about the game,

1183
